Read the following statements about globalisation and identify the key concepts in each. What do you think the writer thinks about globalisation?

Statements

Key Concepts

Writers' feelings

It doesn't matter how far apart we might be geographically, economically or culturally, we're all held tightly together as members of the human race in an all-embracing web.

We are all humans, even if we have different things.

We are all in this together

Jobs are leaving many of the developed nations and moving to developing nations. The money earned helps those developing nations move forward – more jobs, cheaper goods, more profits for research and development. Everybody wins.

Globalisation improves the world economy by moving dollars to developing nations.

Globalisation is helping everyone by investing in poor countries.

I interact with other people who live in different countries when I’m playing computer games.

Games let us communicate with people that we would otherwise not know.

That communication is a sign of globalisation in cyberspace

Countries which are open to external investment are able to develop their economies to generate incomes from exports and raise their standards of living.

External investment can kick-start economic development in some countries (think BRI)

That the BRI and similar projects can contribute to further globalisation.

Of the world's 7 billion people, 214 million are migrants, a phenomenon that has 'internationalised' many cities.

214 million of 7 billion people are migrants

It has made the writer feel that the cities are very diverse.

Young people around the world have adopted international brands and styles without discrimination. Their clothes are influenced by their favourite bands, they sing along to songs they don't understand and support values that don't belong to them. Culture is under siege!

People have taken up brands willy-nilly and without a care of where it came from.

That brands have been able to get a very big market penetration.

Recently we have seen the collapse of undemocratic regimes, improvements in workers' rights, an increase in environmental awareness and responsibility, and an increased awareness of fair trade as a result of advocacy campaigns using social media.

The fall of autocracies has impacted everyone on the planet, and this is somewhat caused by the empowerment of the people.

Gibing people tools ca make a very significant difference.

Sixty-eight million people are served every day in McDonald’s – 33,000 restaurants in 119 countries worldwide.

McDonalds has a global reach.

McDonald's has a unparalleled market penetration - to the tune of 68m people daily in 119 countries.

Globalisation has caused important changes in who makes decisions that affect our lives as multinational companies have more power than national governments.

Multinational governments have lots of power that they may use for good, or for evil.

Multinationals have unparalleled power.

Differences in local conditions require local solutions rather than an externally imposed and globally uniform ‘one size fits all’ solution. 

Local legislation requires peoples to make changes to their products/services.

Law from different places require companies to adapt.
